# Creating your first app with PyQt6

QtWidgets contains a bunch of classes useful for creating an application.

The main modules for Qt are QtWidgets, QtGui and QtCore.

app = QApplication(sys.argv)    # an instance of QApplication passing sys.argv(a list of command line arguments)
*import sys if you need sys.argv

In Qt, all top level widgets are windows

We need to call .show() for a window to be visible/ make it appear during application execution.

A window:
1. Holds application's UI
2. Every application needs at least one but can have more
3. Application exits when the last window is closed

Event loop: When the user interacts with our application, an event is generated and placed on the event queue.
The queue passes events to the even loop, if a waiting event is found, it is passed to the event handler.
Control passes back to the even loop to wait for more events and the process continues.
There can be only one running event loop per application.
QApplication class holds the Qt event loop.

The .exec() method of QApplication starts the event loop.

We define subclass of MainWindow(QMainWindow) because we want to create custom windows.

While creating a subclass of a Qt class, always call super.__init__() to allow the object to be set up.



QtWidget:
QApplication: application handler, holds the event loop of application
QWidget: UI element
QPushButton: just a button, can be initialized with text.
QLabel: text display
QLineEdit: text input box
QVBoxLayout: organizing widgets vertically

QSize: stores width and height parameters


Window Methods:
.setWindowTitle() changes the title of the main window.
.setCentralWidget(<widget>) places a widget at the middle of the window. by default it takes the window itself.


All Widget Methods/Slots:
.setFixedSize(<QSize>) will create a fixed window size.
.setMinimumSize(<QSize>)
.setMaximumSize(<QSize>)
.setCheckable gives widgets like QPushButton on and off states (True/False).
.setChecked can set the initial state of the widget(True/False)
.setEnabled(<bool>)/.setDisabled(<bool>)
.setText(<string>) will change the text in widgets
.setLayout(<layout_object>) takes a layout object as parameter and lays out the widgets within the window accordingly
.setMouseTracking(True)


# PyQt6 Signals, Slots and Events
Signals: notifications emitted by widgets when something happens.
-> notifying when something happens, sending data to provide additional context to what happened.
-> built-in and custom signals

Slots: signal receivers. Any function can be used as a slot by connecting a signal to it.

We use .connect to connect a widget's signal to a slot

Basic Qt Signals:
1. QPushButton.clicked -> triggered when mouse clicks the button and releases the click while it is still within
                            the button. clicked signal sends a checked state argument
2. QPushButton.released -> triggered when mouse clicks the button but it does not matter whether the release happened
                            within the button. released signal does not send checked state argument.
3. QMainWindow.windowTitleChanged   -> triggered when the title of the window is changed.
                                        (only if new title is different from old title)
4. QLineEdit.textChanged    -> triggered when text is changed in the input box, connect passes the text as argument


# Events
-> every interaction that the user has with a Qt application. Qt represents these using event objects.
-> event objects are passed to specific event handlers on the widget where the interaction occurred.
-> Defining custom event handlers, defined just like any other method, but name is specific for the type of event.
-> Eg: QMouseEvent events are created for each and very mouse movement and button click on a widget.
-> Intercept pre-defined events by sub-classing and overriding the handler methods on the class, on the subclass.


Most widgets contain MOUSE event handlers such as mouseMoveEvent, mousePressEvent, mouseReleaseEvent,
mouseDoubleClickEvent. We can build custom interaction by overriding these methods from super class by calling
them in subclass and giving them custom functionality.

Initially, mouseMoveEvent is only triggered when LMB is held down. This can be changed by calling
.setMouseTracking(True) for both window and widget.